<div id="review_3058568016" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3058568016" />
    <a title="Joanka" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/20233424-joanka"><img alt="Joanka" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1476184344p2/20233424.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3058568016?book_show_action=true">Nov 25, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joanka" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joanka" href="/user/show/20233424-joanka">Joanka</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20233424-joanka?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20233424-joanka?shelf=afghanistan">afghanistan</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20233424-joanka?shelf=islamic-countries">islamic-countries</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20233424-joanka?shelf=asia">asia</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3058568016" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8061787581970977827">I was quite distrustful towards this book as somehow in my head an image appeared that it can go wrong in so many ways. A man writing a deeply intimate account of an Afghani woman confession? Can it work? That’s the power of literature – yes, it can. I was swept by the beauty of it, the respect and the truth in the protagonist voice. I loved the language, the imaginary. And finally, I do not agree this novel is in any way ‘too tragic’ or ‘pain porn’, this was and to some extent still is the real</span>
  <span id="freeText8061787581970977827" style="display:none">I was quite distrustful towards this book as somehow in my head an image appeared that it can go wrong in so many ways. A man writing a deeply intimate account of an Afghani woman confession? Can it work? That’s the power of literature – yes, it can. I was swept by the beauty of it, the respect and the truth in the protagonist voice. I loved the language, the imaginary. And finally, I do not agree this novel is in any way ‘too tragic’ or ‘pain porn’, this was and to some extent still is the reality of people living in Afghanistan, both men and women. To be honest I find it quite disrespectful to claim the author wants to gain brownie points with writing about women’s misery. Atiq Rahimi is a refugee from Afghan war and I do believe he wrote a story based on talks and accounts of women, it rings so very true.<br /><br />Finally, as the line in the very beginning suggests, it is a surprisingly universal story about relationships, freedom and the path to it and finally courage to face your demons. I loved it deeply, it touched the right chord in me and I am not surprised it was awarded. The second book by Rahimi didn’t impress me that much but I would read a third one if ever given a chance.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="8061787581970977827" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


