  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_232735758" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/232735758" />
    <a title="Aubrey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4119460-aubrey"><img alt="Aubrey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1635110819p2/4119460.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/232735758?book_show_action=true">Nov 30, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aubrey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aubrey" href="/user/show/4119460-aubrey">Aubrey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=person-of-everything">person-of-everything</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=antidote-think-twice-all">antidote-think-twice-all</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=shorty-short">shorty-short</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=antidote-think-twice-read">antidote-think-twice-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=1-read-on-hand">1-read-on-hand</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=r-goodreads">r-goodreads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=french">french</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=translated">translated</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=person-of-translated">person-of-translated</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer232735758" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3900361387471316457">1.5/5<br/><br/>Imagine a world where a book like this is the only well known piece of literature that is somewhat credibly sourced in the tradition of writing of a country quaintly known as the United States of America. The setting is conflict, the history is cut off at the roots, and the figure of trauma bludgeons each scene, each character, each theme into its most basic conception that is supposedly &quot;spare,&quot; &quot;stark,&quot; and &quot;compact,&quot; but could easily be read instead as &quot;trite,&quot; &quot;stereotypical,&quot; and &quot;conv</span>
  <span id="freeText3900361387471316457" style="display:none">1.5/5<br /><br />Imagine a world where a book like this is the only well known piece of literature that is somewhat credibly sourced in the tradition of writing of a country quaintly known as the United States of America. The setting is conflict, the history is cut off at the roots, and the figure of trauma bludgeons each scene, each character, each theme into its most basic conception that is supposedly "spare," "stark," and "compact," but could easily be read instead as "trite," "stereotypical," and "convenient". You read the book, and it is oh so easy to think, the religion is inhuman, the culture is doomed, the woman must be saved. There is nothing left here of worth, and whatever else of slight significance can be easily replaced by democracy or rehabilitated by capitalism. Now, I'm sure some are going into conniptions over my presumptuousness, while others sputter off into an endless maelstrom of "But, but, but," that is so certain there is not a single plot of land within the entirety of the aforementioned North American nation where there would be such ideological repression, socioeconomic destitution, and almost complete and utter futility when it comes to the idea of a brighter tomorrow. Or perhaps, if there is, it doesn't constitute nearly as much of the country's entire reality as the book implies, and so any reader who limits their reading to that work and that work alone risks coming away with a malignantly insensitive attitude toward an entire population, heritage, and all. However such a case resolves itself, I'm more interested in question of, what makes all this the rule for one reality, and the exception for another? I say question rather than answer because, let's be honest, we all know the latter. It's the asking of the question that will make certain folks uncomfortable enough to make them wonder whether the answer is worth the cost.<br /><br />It doesn't surprise me that Khaled Hosseini and Azar Nafisi figure as two of the three blurbs on the back of this edition, with Yasmina Khadra, actually Mohammed Moulessehoul, rounding out the trio. <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/9840.Jasmine_and_Stars_Reading_More_Than_Lolita_in_Tehran" title="Jasmine and Stars Reading More Than Lolita in Tehran by Fatemeh Keshavarz" rel="nofollow noopener">Jasmine and Stars: Reading More Than Lolita in Tehran</a> picks out the first two as representatives of what has been termed "New Orientalism," where neoliberalism carefully selects cultural envoys that will capture the popular imagination of the target country and are largely immune to criticisms of appropriation/false representation/etc. For this particular work, this "selection" comes literally in the form of this winning what is pretty much the premier literary award of France, a country whose history of anti-Arab bigotry is rather infamous for those paying attention to such matters. When such a text is raised to such heights, my standards are raised accordingly, and while there probably was a measure of texts conforming to a prescribed status quo standard in the case of NDiaye's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13155297.Three_Strong_Women" title="Three Strong Women by Marie NDiaye" rel="nofollow noopener">Three Strong Women</a>, Littell's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3755250.The_Kindly_Ones" title="The Kindly Ones by Jonathan Littell" rel="nofollow noopener">The Kindly Ones</a>, or Duras' <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/275.The_Lover__The_Lover___1_" title="The Lover (The Lover, #1) by Marguerite Duras" rel="nofollow noopener">The Lover</a>, I didn't feel nearly as proselytized to and otherwise ideologically shoved around as I did with this. All in all, if this work had come out along with so many others concerning a similar part of the world during a similar time and had to compete for the public eye alongside texts written on the level of, say, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/46439.Gate_of_the_Sun_Bab_Al_Shams" title="Gate of the Sun Bab Al-Shams by Elias Khoury" rel="nofollow noopener">Gate of the Sun: Bab Al-Shams</a>, I wouldn't mind it nearly as much. As it currently stands, however, should one fill in the literary void that 'common sense' dictates has to be the case it comes to literature of Afghanistan, you have a work here that certainly has its place in the general spread, but certainly does not serve as a "universal" text for the "faceless and voiceless." This far into my reading career, I have my doubts as to whether such a work could ever exist.<br /><br />It literally took me a decade to track down a copy of this, and all I can say is, I'm glad I got it over with sooner rather than later. Much has changed since 2008, 2010, but if there's anything that can be said about the US and another nations who can never rest easy knowing that there's entities out there who don't welcome disaster capitalism with open arms and smiling faces, it's that the names may change but the greed stays the same. These days, the popular target of paranoia and scorn is once again China, and it will be mildly interesting to see what kind of NYT bestselling publications are spawned from that particular kind of fearmongering, if only out of a sense of morbid curiosity. I have no doubt that Rahimi's text portrays a particular scenario/emotional confluence that could well have existed at one time or another, but to have it take center stage in the literary sector is rather status quo convenient, just as the hypothetical scenario of the only internationally recognized US literature being pieces that hail from the reservations would be the exact opposite. If someone reads this text and is inspired to delve much more deeply into Afghani literature and associated subjects with a true commitment to compassionate engagement and self-reflexive critical literacy, so much the better. If, on the other hand, they read this, see only what hegemonic paradigms they had already picked up from newscast propaganda, and leave it forever at that, that doesn't bode well for the kind of literature that wins grand prizes for being "the best and most imaginative prose work of the year," does it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3900361387471316457" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


