  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3478422963" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3478422963" />
    <a title="Fiction O Phile" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/112327731-fiction-o-phile"><img alt="Fiction O Phile" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1590499121p2/112327731.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3478422963?book_show_action=true">Aug 05, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Fiction O Phile" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Fiction O Phile" href="/user/show/112327731-fiction-o-phile">Fiction O Phile</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3478422963" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13999973967379927371">🍁 &quot;If all religion is to do with revelation, the revelation of a truth, then, my sang-e saboor, our story is a religion too! Our very own religion!&quot;<br/>.<br/>.<br/>📖 You have experienced Mariam and Laila&apos;s life through Khaled Hosseini&apos; s &apos;A thousand splendid suns&apos;. Here in this historical fiction Rahimi has unfolded those harsh Jihad days of Afghanistan, where an anonymous woman was abused sexually and mentally day by day as she had broken her silence and ranted her sufferings. As her Jihadist husband became </span>
  <span id="freeText13999973967379927371" style="display:none">🍁 "If all religion is to do with revelation, the revelation of a truth, then, my sang-e saboor, our story is a religion too! Our very own religion!"<br />.<br />.<br />📖 You have experienced Mariam and Laila's life through Khaled Hosseini' s 'A thousand splendid suns'. Here in this historical fiction Rahimi has unfolded those harsh Jihad days of Afghanistan, where an anonymous woman was abused sexually and mentally day by day as she had broken her silence and ranted her sufferings. As her Jihadist husband became a living corpse, she ranted about her experiences with that patience stone which was her living corpse husband. The entire story unfolds in one room, where an unnamed woman nurses her badly injured husband, who lies motionless, wordless, and helpless. Here, Rahimi has broached a great Afghan taboo, the notion of a woman as a sexual being. This novel’s greatest achievement is in giving voice, giving voice to those who, as the fable goes, suffer the most and cry out the least. Her father in law told her about a black stone portrayed as Mecca, "You talk to it, and talk to it. And the stone listens, absorbing all your words, all your secrets, until one fine day it explodes. Shatters into tiny pieces." , so she kept ranting about her sufferings to her motionless husband so that he would explode by absorbing all her sorrows and sufferings.<br />.<br />.<br />🍁 From Hosseini's voice - as her husband lies before her like a stone—indeed like the legendary titular stone, which absorbs the anguish of all who confess to it—the woman suddenly finds herself free from all restraint and her monologues reach a fevered pitch. What pours out of her is not only a brave and shocking confession, but a savage indictment of war, the brutality of men, and the religious, marital, and cultural norms that continually assault Afghan women, leaving them with no recourse but to absorb without complaint, like a patience stone. Rahimi’s nameless heroine is a conduit, a living vessel for the grievances of millions of women like her, women who have been objectified, marginalized, scorned, beaten, ridiculed, silenced. In The Patience Stone, they have their say at last.<br /> .<br /> .<br />🍁 Don't fall in the trap of the book's rating and reviews on Goodreads. You can't miss those monologues, just like Hosseini, Rahimi will also shatter your heart into pieces.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13999973967379927371" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


