<div id="review_148290648" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/148290648" />
    <a title="Hiba Essa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3707170-hiba-essa"><img alt="Hiba Essa" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1308913979p2/3707170.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/148290648?book_show_action=true">Feb 15, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hiba Essa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hiba Essa" href="/user/show/3707170-hiba-essa">Hiba Essa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780701184162" href="/book/show/7661722-the-patience-stone">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer148290648" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5766263208033060966">Beautifully written but a lot of violence and crude words are not always necessary to make a point.<br/><br/>Winner of the prestigious Goncourt Prize in France, an Afghani writer with an introduction by Khalid Hosseini - I was thrilled to start reading and managed to finish it in one evening.<br/><br/>This short novel is incredibly deep in the psychological and social exploration of a &quot;typical&quot; afghani woman, whose husband, a Jihad warrior, has been injured. As he lays there in the coma she uses him as a sang-e-sab</span>
  <span id="freeText5766263208033060966" style="display:none">Beautifully written but a lot of violence and crude words are not always necessary to make a point.<br /><br />Winner of the prestigious Goncourt Prize in France, an Afghani writer with an introduction by Khalid Hosseini - I was thrilled to start reading and managed to finish it in one evening.<br /><br />This short novel is incredibly deep in the psychological and social exploration of a "typical" afghani woman, whose husband, a Jihad warrior, has been injured. As he lays there in the coma she uses him as a sang-e-saboor, a magic stone, a patience stone, that absorbs the trouble of those who confide in it. <br /><br />Its definitely not an upbeat story and not for the delicate stomach.<br />This book gives voice to those who suffer the most but cry out the least. <br /><br />In the Patience Stone, they have their say - at last.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="5766263208033060966" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


